  1. The null hyphothesis: the coefficient of Age equals zero, that means the p-value of the test for Age is higher than significace level. If the significance level is 0.05. The Pr of Age coefficient is 0.02389 < 0.05. So there is difference with the Age in the linear model and without the age coefficient in the linear model. So we reject null hypothesis. In the above result and conclude that Age coefficient doesnt equal zero.

  2. The null hyphothesis: the coefficient of Abdomen equals zero, that means the p-value of the test for Abdomen is higher than significace level. If the significance level is 0.05. The Pr of Abdomen coefficient is 2e-16 < 0.05. So there is difference with the Abdomen in the linear model and without the Abdomen coefficient in the linear model. So we reject null hypothesis. In the above result and conclude that Abdomen coefficient doesnt equal zero.

  3. Draw a residual plot, with the fitted values on the x-axis, and the residuals on the y-axis. Through the below residual plot, we could conclude that the plot doesnt vialate the key assumptions of the linear model: a) mean function is lenier, b) variance is constant, c) response distribution is normal. So linear model is suitable to this data.

  1. Draw a scatter plot of ten body circumference measurement. We can see from the plot that chest_cir and abdomen_cir has positive correlationship. Their plot is close to linear thin line. The person with higher chest_cir usually has highter abdomen_cir. The slope of the plot indicates how much chest_cir might increase when abdomen_cir increase. For example, the slope in plot between chest_cir (Y axis) and abdomen (X axis) is bigger than the plot between ankle_cir (Y axis) and abdomen_cir (X axis). That means chest_cir increase more than ankle_cir with the same amount of abdomen_cir.
